

We think in images, not in words; all right; when, however, we compose,recall, or refashion at midnight in our <122> brain something we wish to sayin tomorrow's sermon, or have said to Dolly in a recent dream, or wish wehad said to that impertinent proctor twenty years ago, the images we thinkin are, of course, verbal--and even audible if we happen to be lonely andold. We do not usually think in words, since most of life is mimodrama, butwe certainly do imagine words when we need them, just as